As Financial Literacy Month comes to a close, we thought we would ask: Why do you think teens are budgeting less today? Teens reported in a recent Allstate Foundation / Junior Achievement USA / JA Worldwide Poll that they agree money management is important, but they aren't doing it. From 2011 to 2012, there was a three-fold increase in the number of teens who report not budgeting or managing their money (10% in 2011 vs. 34% in 2012).

The best elements of all the previous logos are combined to emphasize the human dimensions of the personality of Allstate.
Business people are added to the hands to represent our newest line of insurance - Commercial Insurance.
The Good Hands tagline is added to the slant "A" Allstate to create a strong professional look.
Leo Burnett, a long-term advertising partner, contemporizes the house and car with a new format.
Allstate hires an outside design firm to create a new logo that will represent Allstate as contemporary, strong, imaginative, progressive and vigorous.
A new variation of the logo is created with a family in the hands to symbolize the newly-established Allstate Life Insurance Company.
The Allstate logo is reformatted to further emphasize the powerful brand name and slogan.
Allstate is a major sponsor on television; it made sense to incorporate a television shape into the Good Hands logo.
Space limitations are the impetus for designing a cleaner, smaller, easier to read logo.
A car and a home are added to the hands symbol to symbolize the lines of insurance Allstate sold.
Allstate streamlines its logo to make it easier to read and reproduce.
Allstate creates the "Illustrator Policy." It uses simpler language and illustrations so customers can more easily understand policy language and coverage.
Allstate creates the "Illustrator Policy." It uses simpler language and illustrations so customers can more easily understand policy language and coverage.
Allstate develops a series of training courses for women agents to replace men on military leave. Women also begin handling claims.
The direct-mail sales method changes to Allstate-agent representation with the opening of the first Allstate sales location in a Chicago Sears.
At the Chicago World's Fair, Richard Roskam becomes Allstate's first agent when he sets up a card table in the Sears exhibit and is swamped with applications.
William Lehnertz becomes Allstate's first policy holder
